AN ACT relating to education; requiring the Department of Education to transfer
certain data concerning pupils to [the Division of State Library,
Archives and Public Records of the Department of Administration;] an
archive maintained by the Department; requiring the [Division]
Department to destroy such data after a certain period of time; and
providing other matters properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law requires the Department of Education to establish an automated system of
2 accountability information that records and tracks certain data relating to the education
3 system, including, without limitation, a system of unique identification for each pupil and the
4 results of the achievement of pupils. (NRS 385A.800) Existing law requires the board of
5 trustees of each school district to collect and provide certain data concerning pupils, as
6 prescribed by the Superintendent of Public Instruction, to the Department of Education. (NRS
7 385A.810, 385A.820)
8 [Existing law establishes: (1) the Division of State Library, Archives and Public Records
9 of the Department of Administration; (2) the position of State Library, Archives and Public
10 Records Administrator; and (3) the duties of the Administrator. (NRS 232.213, 378.010-
11 378.130)] This bill requires the Department [of Education] to: (1) not later than 1 year after a
12 pupil graduates from a high school or otherwise ceases enrollment in a public school in this
13 State, transfer any data concerning the pupil to [the Division;] an archive of data concerning
14 pupils that is maintained by the Department; and (2) redact any personally identifiable
15 information , except for the birth date of the pupil, from the data before making such a
16 transfer.
17 Existing law: (1) creates the Committee to Approve Schedules for the Retention and
18 Disposition of Official State Records; (2) requires the Committee to review and approve or
19 disapprove the schedules for the retention and disposition of the official state records of each
20 agency, board and commission that is required to create such schedules; and (3) prohibits an
21 official state record from being disposed of in a manner other than the schedule approved by
22 the Committee. (NRS 239.073, 239.077, 239.080, 378.320) This bill : [requires:] (1) provides
23 that these provisions do not apply to any data concerning pupils that is transferred to [the
24 Division] an archive maintained by the Department pursuant to this bill ; [be redacted
25 before being transferred;] and (2) requires the [Division] Department to destroy such data 10
26 years after [receiving any data pursuant to this bill.] a pupil whose data was transferred to
27 such an archive reaches 22 years of age.

Senate Amendment No. 266 to Senate Bill No. 445 Page 4
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. Chapter 388 of NRS is hereby amended by adding thereto a new
2 section to read as follows:
3 1. The Department shall, not later than 1 year after a pupil graduates from
4 a high school or otherwise ceases enrollment in a public school in this State,
5 transfer any data concerning the pupil to [the Division.] an archive of data
6 concerning pupils that is maintained by the Department. Any personally
7 identifiable information , not including the birth date of the pupil, must be
8 redacted from any data concerning the pupil before being transferred to the
9 [Division.] archive.
10 2. Notwithstanding the provisions of NRS 239.080 and 378.320, the
11 [Division] Department shall, 10 years after [receiving any data transferred to the
12 Division pursuant to subsection 1,] a pupil whose data was transferred pursuant
13 to subsection 1 reaches 22 years of age, destroy the data.
14 3. As used in this section:
15 (a) “Data” means any data concerning a pupil that is collected by, or
16 provided to, the Department pursuant to NRS 385A.800, 385A.810 or 385A.820,
17 including, without limitation, a number assigned to a pupil as part of a system of
18 unique identification of each pupil.
19 (b) [“Division” means the Division of State Library, Archives and Public
20 Records of the Department of Administration.
21 (c)] “Personally identifiable information” has the meaning ascribed to it in
22 34 C.F.R. § 99.3.

